WEBVTT

00:11.512 --> 00:14.247
♪ Sometimes the world
looks perfect ♪

00:14.280 --> 00:17.417
♪ Nothin' to rearrange ♪

00:17.450 --> 00:20.086
♪ Sometimes you just
get a feelin' ♪

00:20.120 --> 00:24.090
♪ Like you need some
kind of change ♪

00:24.124 --> 00:28.128
♪ No matter what
the odds are this time ♪

00:28.161 --> 00:30.597
♪ Nothing's gonna stand
in my way ♪

00:30.631 --> 00:34.234
♪ This flame in my heart
like a long lost friend ♪

00:34.267 --> 00:37.504
♪ Gives every dark street
a light at the end ♪

00:39.372 --> 00:41.642
♪ Standing tall ♪

00:41.675 --> 00:45.512
♪ On the wings of my dream ♪

00:45.546 --> 00:48.515
♪ Rise and fall ♪

00:48.549 --> 00:52.719
♪ On the wings of my dream ♪

00:52.753 --> 00:55.789
♪ The rain and thunder,
the wind and haze ♪

00:55.822 --> 00:59.526
♪ I'm bound
for better days ♪

00:59.560 --> 01:02.462
♪ It's my life and my dream ♪

01:02.495 --> 01:06.232
♪ Nothing's going
to stop me now ♪

01:06.266 --> 01:09.102
♪ It's my life
and my dream ♪

01:09.135 --> 01:12.072
♪ Nothing's going
to stop me now ♪

01:19.746 --> 01:22.215
♪ Nothing's going to
stop me now ♪

01:36.697 --> 01:38.599
LARRY:
Slowly.

01:38.632 --> 01:41.467
Now you're coming up
to the step, so take it slow.

01:41.502 --> 01:43.604
You're getting closer.
A little closer.

01:43.637 --> 01:48.509
You're close.
You're very, very close.

01:48.542 --> 01:49.743
You're down the step.

01:52.178 --> 01:55.148
You don't say.

01:55.181 --> 01:58.418
Now, you wanna bring
it straight down here
and we'll just swing it in.

01:58.451 --> 02:00.687
Straight down here,
we'll swing it right in here.

02:00.721 --> 02:04.457
Come straight down
and we'll swing it in.

02:07.628 --> 02:12.432
Cousin, why I make all the push
and you are just stand there
with... Just say:

02:12.465 --> 02:15.168
"Just take that baby
and swing it on..."?

02:17.638 --> 02:20.306
Balki, somebody has
to be in charge.

02:20.340 --> 02:22.776
Somebody has to have a plan.
That's me.

02:22.809 --> 02:26.379
Somebody else has to carry out
the plan. That's you.

02:26.412 --> 02:28.815
I get it. As long as it's equal.

02:28.849 --> 02:31.652
All right.

02:31.685 --> 02:34.688
Straight down here
and we'll swing it in.

02:34.721 --> 02:36.456
Go easy, go easy.
Take your time.

02:36.489 --> 02:37.858
Good, good. OK.

02:37.891 --> 02:40.260
Swing it around.
Come towards me.

02:40.293 --> 02:41.962
Towards me. Slow, slow.

02:41.995 --> 02:43.697
That's good. OK.

02:43.730 --> 02:45.231
‐Now...
‐WOMAN: Balki.

02:45.265 --> 02:47.233
[LARRY GRUNTS]

02:47.267 --> 02:48.735
‐Gina.
‐Balki, please,
you have to help me.

02:48.769 --> 02:50.904
‐Of course I help you.
‐What about me?

02:50.937 --> 02:54.708
You're right, I'm being rude.
Gina, this my cousin, Larry.

02:54.741 --> 02:58.311
And Cousin Larry,
this Gina Morelli
from my citizenship class.

02:58.344 --> 03:00.981
She's from Italy.

03:01.014 --> 03:02.949
She's Italian.

03:02.983 --> 03:04.384
Oh.

03:04.417 --> 03:06.787
‐This my cousin, Larry.
‐Hello.

03:06.820 --> 03:09.923
I would shake your hand,
but I'm being crushed
by a refrigerator.

03:09.956 --> 03:11.424
‐GINA: Oh.
‐Thank you.

03:14.928 --> 03:18.565
Well, you're very strong
for your condition.

03:18.599 --> 03:20.400
[GINA SOBBING]

03:20.433 --> 03:23.970
Was it something I said?

03:24.004 --> 03:27.508
My husband is a truck driver
and he's in Texas now.

03:27.541 --> 03:30.577
While he's gone,
I get evicted from my apartment.

03:30.611 --> 03:33.379
I have no money
and I can't get a hold of him.

03:33.413 --> 03:36.950
Balki is my only friend in this
country, so I came here.

03:36.983 --> 03:39.886
Well, you did the right thing,
Gina. We'll take care of you.

03:39.920 --> 03:43.423
‐Won't we, cousin?
‐Of course we will.

03:43.456 --> 03:45.826
What did you have in mind?

03:45.859 --> 03:49.863
She stay in the apartment
until her husband gets back.

03:49.896 --> 03:52.498
Oh. Oh. Oh. Uh....

03:52.533 --> 03:56.002
I don't know.
Well, where would she sleep?

03:56.036 --> 03:58.438
‐I'll give her the couch.
‐Well, that's no good.

03:58.471 --> 04:02.442
She'd have no privacy.
She has to have her own room.

04:02.475 --> 04:04.811
Cousin says that you have to
have his bedroom.

04:04.845 --> 04:06.680
Wha...?

04:06.713 --> 04:09.583
Didn't I tell you
he was a prince?

04:09.616 --> 04:13.720
Oh, you are more than that.
You are a saint.

04:13.754 --> 04:17.591
You're going to love it at
our house. He has a blanket
that plugs into the wall.

04:17.624 --> 04:20.560
You're kidding me.
What's that for?

04:20.594 --> 04:22.428
Beats the socks off of me.

04:29.503 --> 04:31.437
BALKI:
Good night.

04:31.471 --> 04:34.741
[GINA AND BALKI SPEAKING
IN ITALIAN]

04:39.580 --> 04:44.417
Cousin, you don't mind
I put the television
in the bedroom of Gina?

04:44.450 --> 04:47.954
She has my room,
why shouldn't she have my TV?

04:47.988 --> 04:50.691
I'd put her in my will,
but she already has
everything I own.

04:54.060 --> 04:57.564
Cousin, if you don't want Gina
here, why you didn't say so?

04:57.598 --> 05:00.433
It's a little inconvenient,
but I'll get used to it.

05:00.466 --> 05:02.803
I'm glad we can help out.

05:02.836 --> 05:04.437
Let's hit the sack.

05:20.587 --> 05:23.089
What are those?

05:23.123 --> 05:26.927
These are my Spider‐Man pajamas.

05:26.960 --> 05:29.630
Let me rephrase that.

05:29.663 --> 05:32.733
Why are you wearing those?

05:32.766 --> 05:35.401
Because my He‐Man pajamas
are in the laundry.

05:38.605 --> 05:41.708
I had to ask.

05:41.742 --> 05:43.877
[BALKI YAWNING]

05:50.784 --> 05:52.719
‐Do you usually sleep
on that side?
‐Yes.

05:52.753 --> 05:54.688
‐Why don't I go...?
‐I go to that side.

05:54.721 --> 05:55.656
No, I will go to that side.

05:55.689 --> 05:58.458
I don't mind sleeping
on that side of the bed.

05:58.491 --> 06:00.994
I mind arguing about sleeping
on that side of the bed.

06:19.680 --> 06:22.148
You know, I really admire you.

06:22.182 --> 06:24.184
Why is that?

06:24.217 --> 06:27.621
Well, because, first,
you're willing to give
up your bedroom...

06:27.654 --> 06:28.855
...to a woman I hardly know.

06:38.498 --> 06:41.702
And then, for me, your friend,
you're willing to sleep on
the hot side of the bed.

06:49.543 --> 06:54.480
What do you mean,
"the hot side of the bed"?

06:54.515 --> 06:57.918
Well, about 6:00 in the morning,

06:57.951 --> 07:00.687
see that little hole
in the drapes?

07:00.721 --> 07:04.157
The sun come through that
and it bores a hole...

07:04.190 --> 07:05.926
...right through your head
like a laser beam.

07:15.902 --> 07:19.973
OK, other side. Move. Let's
go.

07:20.006 --> 07:20.874
[LARRY SIGHS]

07:26.279 --> 07:27.814
‐Good night.
‐Good night.

07:33.887 --> 07:35.221
What's in my face?

07:39.993 --> 07:42.896
Dimitri.
He always sleeps with me.

07:42.929 --> 07:46.567
Ding‐ding‐dang...

07:46.600 --> 07:47.467
Not tonight.

07:58.779 --> 08:02.883
I say my prayers now.

08:02.916 --> 08:05.986
God, bless Cousin Larry

08:06.019 --> 08:08.655
and Gina and the new baby.

08:08.689 --> 08:11.525
And please watch over Dimitri,
who's sleeping on the floor...

08:11.558 --> 08:13.694
...for the first time
in his whole young life.

08:13.727 --> 08:14.795
Amen.

08:25.872 --> 08:26.973
[LARRY SIGHS]

08:31.244 --> 08:33.914
Balki, I'm sorry.

08:37.317 --> 08:39.184
I'm not the one you threw
on the floor.

08:57.938 --> 09:02.843
I'm sorry, Dimitri.

09:02.876 --> 09:03.944
Please forgive me.

09:11.317 --> 09:15.055
Well, I just wanted to thank you
for what you're doing for Gina.

09:18.324 --> 09:20.927
Well, I guess you have to
do whatever you can...

09:20.961 --> 09:25.899
...for someone who's carrying
a new life.

09:25.932 --> 09:29.803
‐A new, overdue life.
‐Hmm?

09:29.836 --> 09:32.606
The baby was two weeks ago late.

09:32.639 --> 09:34.007
‐Good night.
‐Good night.

10:03.770 --> 10:07.140
All right, rest period is over.

10:07.173 --> 10:10.877
All right, now let's go through
this plan one more time.

10:10.911 --> 10:12.713
‐Do we have to?
‐Yes, we have to.

10:12.746 --> 10:14.715
We have to be prepared
when the baby comes.

10:14.748 --> 10:17.017
I'm very unhappy
with the time it's taking us...

10:17.050 --> 10:20.320
...to get from the bed
out the door.

10:20.353 --> 10:22.823
[WHISPERING]
Cousin, it's 1:00
in the morning.

10:22.856 --> 10:24.925
Already we do 10 times this.

10:24.958 --> 10:27.728
‐Let Gina sleep.
‐OK, OK, all right.

10:27.761 --> 10:32.032
We'll probably make better
time without her anyway.

10:32.065 --> 10:34.200
Gina? Gina? Wake up.

10:34.234 --> 10:36.069
You can go to sleep now.

10:36.102 --> 10:39.272
Ohh. You're a saint.

10:39.305 --> 10:41.407
Yeah, that's good.
Get her up, get her up.

10:41.441 --> 10:43.443
Yeah, swing her around.
Swing her around.

10:43.476 --> 10:46.046
Straight on back.
Just straight on back there.
Good.

10:46.079 --> 10:48.014
OK. Yes.

10:48.048 --> 10:52.218
Gina, Balki and me.

10:54.387 --> 10:57.457
Cousin, can you do without me
too? I know my part.

10:57.490 --> 11:01.394
You're not bugging out on me
now. This is all your fault, you
know.

11:01.427 --> 11:04.030
Why didn't you tell me
she was pregnant?

11:04.064 --> 11:06.032
What did you think it was,
a bee sting?

11:12.205 --> 11:14.474
You are wasting valuable
rehearsal time.

11:14.508 --> 11:17.978
Cousin, what the big deal is?

11:18.011 --> 11:21.848
In my country, every time
a woman has a baby, she
doesn't run to the hospital.

11:21.882 --> 11:24.718
If every woman did that,
we'd have to have two hospitals.

11:27.420 --> 11:30.490
In Mypos, to have a baby is very
natural.

11:30.524 --> 11:34.360
The woman is working
in the field, she takes
a short break...

11:38.331 --> 11:42.803
...she has her baby,
and then she cooks
dinner for 11 men.

11:45.138 --> 11:48.174
Look, this is America.
We make things a lot
more complicated.

11:48.208 --> 11:50.476
When a woman has a baby,
she has to go to the hospital.

11:50.511 --> 11:52.412
That is a rule.

11:52.445 --> 11:54.981
And to get to the hospital,
you have to have a plan.

11:55.015 --> 11:58.819
‐Now, do you have a plan?
‐Well, of course I do.
Don't be ridiculous.

12:00.320 --> 12:01.955
And what is it?

12:01.988 --> 12:04.925
I don't know.

12:04.958 --> 12:06.793
Fine. Then we'll go with mine.

12:06.827 --> 12:09.495
Now, let's take it from
the top one last time.

12:18.004 --> 12:20.306
All right, we're in bed.
We're sleeping.

12:20.340 --> 12:22.308
Sleep, sleep, sleep.

12:22.342 --> 12:26.346
‐Gina comes out of the bedroom.
‐Waddle, waddle, waddle.

12:26.379 --> 12:29.149
She says, "It's time."
Now, what do we do?

12:29.182 --> 12:32.018
I get the suitcase out of the
closet and you call the
hospital.

12:32.052 --> 12:34.020
All right. Ready?

12:34.054 --> 12:35.856
‐Go.
‐Wait.

12:35.889 --> 12:39.560
What?

12:39.593 --> 12:42.495
Why do I always have
to get the suitcase out
of the closet?

12:42.529 --> 12:46.166
Because I am
the better communicator,
so I call the hospital.

12:46.199 --> 12:49.469
You are much better at lifting,
so you get the suitcase.

12:53.273 --> 12:56.309
How do you know
I'm not the better communicator?

12:56.342 --> 12:57.878
Have you ever listened
to yourself?

13:03.116 --> 13:07.087
‐Not while I'm talking.
‐Well, there you go.

13:07.120 --> 13:10.123
Well....

13:10.156 --> 13:15.028
I want to make the phone call.

13:15.061 --> 13:17.397
OK, fine. You call the
hospital.

13:17.430 --> 13:20.466
Now can we get on with this?

13:20.500 --> 13:23.369
‐Ready? Go.
‐Wait.

13:23.403 --> 13:27.007
What?

13:27.040 --> 13:28.575
I don't know the phone number.

13:28.609 --> 13:31.878
It's on the list of emergency
numbers next to the phone.

13:31.912 --> 13:34.948
Take my word for it. It's there.

13:34.981 --> 13:39.452
Now, can we do this
before the kid graduates
from college?

13:39.485 --> 13:41.121
Ready?

13:41.154 --> 13:42.222
Go.

13:46.627 --> 13:48.862
Beep‐beep‐beep‐beep‐beep.

13:48.895 --> 13:53.299
Hello, hospital? Baby's coming.

13:53.333 --> 13:55.869
‐I did it.
‐Brilliant.

13:55.902 --> 13:57.638
Now, you get the jackets,

13:57.671 --> 14:01.608
I get the map, and we are out.

14:01.642 --> 14:03.944
I was right.
We're much faster without Gina.

14:06.547 --> 14:09.282
‐Good night.
‐All right.

14:09.315 --> 14:12.085
‐You get some sleep.
‐What about you?

14:12.118 --> 14:13.920
I won't be sleeping tonight.

14:18.291 --> 14:22.128
Someone has got to be awake,
alert, prepared.

14:24.364 --> 14:28.201
I guess I'll have to bear
that burden alone.

14:28.234 --> 14:29.135
I guess so.

14:36.543 --> 14:39.946
This must have been how
Eisenhower felt just
before D‐day.

14:43.584 --> 14:47.153
All around him, the troops
sleeping. But not Ike.

14:49.523 --> 14:52.325
He knew that one single
mistake

14:52.358 --> 14:54.961
could change the course
of world history.

14:57.731 --> 15:00.133
Was this before or after
Ike met Tina Turner?

15:10.443 --> 15:11.477
Before.

15:22.623 --> 15:26.727
Balki, wake up.

15:26.760 --> 15:29.029
Balki, it's time.

15:29.062 --> 15:32.232
‐Gina? It's time?
‐Yes.

15:32.265 --> 15:35.702
Ah, Gina, how exciting.
A little baby.

15:35.736 --> 15:37.704
LARRY:
Mm?

15:37.738 --> 15:41.007
‐Why is the light on?
‐The baby's coming, Larry.

15:41.041 --> 15:45.045
What baby? Who are you?

15:45.078 --> 15:47.748
Why am I holding a sheep?

15:47.781 --> 15:50.283
He doesn't wake up well.

15:50.316 --> 15:52.686
Cousin, it's Gina.
Remember the plan?

15:55.455 --> 15:57.390
The plan? Yes, of course
I remember the plan.

15:57.423 --> 16:00.360
It's my plan. All right, no need
to worry.

16:00.393 --> 16:02.362
First, babies take a long time.

16:02.395 --> 16:05.732
‐Well, Larry, I've been
in labor a long time.
‐Why didn't you tell us?

16:05.766 --> 16:08.535
Well, I didn't wanna bother you.
You were up so late.

16:08.569 --> 16:10.671
All right. Don't panic.

16:12.472 --> 16:13.674
Go!

16:18.645 --> 16:20.681
‐BALKI: Are you all right?
‐Yes, yes. I'm OK.

16:20.714 --> 16:23.016
‐What are you doing?
‐Calling the hospital.

16:23.049 --> 16:25.719
Calling the hospital is my job.
You get the suitcase.

16:25.752 --> 16:28.722
But I called the hospital
last time.

16:28.755 --> 16:31.625
I gave you a chance to prove
you were a good communicator.

16:31.658 --> 16:33.594
[IMITATES BALKI]
"Hello, hospital?
Baby is coming."

16:33.627 --> 16:35.562
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Cavemen are more articulate.

16:35.596 --> 16:37.764
Could you please hurry? Ohh!

16:37.798 --> 16:42.402
Hello, hospital? The baby is
coming.

16:42.435 --> 16:43.737
Brilliant.

16:43.770 --> 16:46.206
‐I forgot to tell...
‐Larry, there's no time.

16:46.239 --> 16:49.342
We get to the hospital,
they probably figure out why I'm
there.

16:49.375 --> 16:51.645
Good thinking.
OK, all right. No need to
panic.

16:51.678 --> 16:55.048
Everything is under
control, all right?

16:55.081 --> 16:59.285
I get the map and we are gone.

16:59.319 --> 17:00.220
Yes!

17:05.125 --> 17:06.827
My keys, my keys.
Where are my keys?

17:06.859 --> 17:09.128
‐They're in your pants.
‐Where are my pants?

17:09.162 --> 17:12.265
‐They're in the closet.
‐Where is the closet?
Where's the closet?

17:12.298 --> 17:13.666
‐Cousin, cousin.
‐Look, look.

17:13.700 --> 17:16.136
We can't get
to the hospital without my keys.

17:16.169 --> 17:17.604
‐BALKI: Cousin.
‐Don't "cousin" me now.

17:17.637 --> 17:19.439
Look, look,
I don't have my keys.

17:19.472 --> 17:21.808
I don't have my pants.
I can't do this.

17:21.842 --> 17:24.243
She will just have to have the
baby at some other time.

17:24.277 --> 17:26.079
Why don't you help me?

17:30.416 --> 17:34.821
Oh. Oh, I see. You're
trying to make me look
bad in front of Gina.

17:34.855 --> 17:37.190
Where is Gina?
Where is the mother?

17:37.223 --> 17:40.426
We can't do this
without the mother! [PANTING]

17:40.460 --> 17:43.263
Cousin, someday you'll
forgive me for this.

17:50.771 --> 17:53.239
Feel better?

17:53.273 --> 17:54.340
No.

17:56.777 --> 17:58.545
Can we go have a baby now?

17:58.579 --> 18:02.148
OK. I'll follow you.

18:02.182 --> 18:04.484
Where are you going?

18:04.518 --> 18:06.753
‐To the hospital.
‐Right, yes.

18:06.787 --> 18:08.288
Gina, there you are.
Thank God.

18:13.927 --> 18:16.763
BALKI:
Gina, lay down here
and try to relax.

18:16.797 --> 18:18.398
[TIRES SCREECHING]

18:23.604 --> 18:26.707
Keep breathing.
Keep breathing.

18:26.740 --> 18:28.909
You're doing good.

18:28.942 --> 18:33.213
I can't keep this up.
I think I'm hyperventilating.

18:33.246 --> 18:35.381
Cousin, I was talking to Gina.

18:37.651 --> 18:39.653
‐[HORN HONKING]
‐[LARRY GRUNTS]

18:39.686 --> 18:42.756
What's the matter, buddy?
Late for your accident?

18:42.789 --> 18:45.659
Jeez! Did you see that guy?

18:45.692 --> 18:49.863
How does somebody like
that get to be a cop?

18:49.896 --> 18:53.166
GINA: How much further
to the hospital, Larry?

18:53.199 --> 18:56.503
Look, I am doing the best I can.
I've got my hands full up here.

18:56.537 --> 18:58.705
Every nutcase in town
is on the road tonight.

18:58.739 --> 19:03.176
The heater doesn't work
and my map reader is back
there with you.

19:03.209 --> 19:06.412
‐GINA: I'm sorry.
‐What...?

19:06.446 --> 19:09.716
Do you think you could go
a little faster? I think
the baby almost here.

19:09.750 --> 19:12.385
I am going as fast as I can.

19:12.418 --> 19:14.955
You can go a little
faster. Just stick your
foot on the pedal and push.

19:14.988 --> 19:17.758
I haven't forgotten
how to drive.

19:17.791 --> 19:19.793
Well, you did when you
first got in the car.

19:19.826 --> 19:21.795
[GINA GROANS]

19:21.828 --> 19:26.199
All right, all right, I'm going
faster. Are you happy now?

19:26.232 --> 19:29.369
‐Wasn't that the turnoff
to the hospital?
‐Go fast, read signs.

19:29.402 --> 19:31.838
What do you people want from me?

19:31.872 --> 19:34.307
‐Watch out for that bump.
‐I see it.

19:34.340 --> 19:35.776
[LARRY GRUNTS]

19:35.809 --> 19:37.410
‐GINA: Ohh!
‐BALKI: Ohh!

19:37.443 --> 19:39.946
Well, that certainly
speeded things up.

19:39.980 --> 19:42.983
Cousin, I think I'm going to
have to deliver this baby
myself.

19:43.016 --> 19:46.452
‐No. No, you can't do that.
‐Well, do you want to do it?

19:46.486 --> 19:49.523
GINA:
Somebody better do it.

19:49.556 --> 19:54.227
Oh! Aah! All right, I can't see.
We're all going to die.

19:54.260 --> 19:57.964
Gina, let go
of Cousin Larry's head.

19:57.998 --> 19:59.332
[TIRES SCREECHING]

19:59.365 --> 20:02.235
Cousin. Cousin, stop. Stop now.

20:02.268 --> 20:03.436
Gina having her baby now.

20:05.806 --> 20:09.610
‐Oh, my God.
‐[GINA SHOUTS IN ITALIAN]

20:09.643 --> 20:13.379
What is she saying? What's
she saying? Would somebody
back there talk to me?

20:13.413 --> 20:15.281
[BABY CRYING]

20:15.315 --> 20:16.416
Who was that?

20:20.587 --> 20:23.223
Hello, baby.
Welcome to America.

20:35.368 --> 20:36.903
Oh, my God.

20:36.937 --> 20:38.739
[HORN HONKING]

20:58.659 --> 21:00.794
Well, little boy,
we've had a big day.

21:07.601 --> 21:11.004
We witnessed
the miracle of birth.

21:11.037 --> 21:14.474
You witnessed the miracle
of birth. I took one look
and passed out.

21:15.976 --> 21:17.744
Of course, the good news...

21:17.778 --> 21:19.980
...is that while I was
unconscious, I couldn't
behave like a lunatic.

21:23.049 --> 21:26.987
It was all there.
Ike would've been proud.

21:27.020 --> 21:30.423
A perfect plan to get Gina
to the hospital. Ha‐ha.

21:30.456 --> 21:32.659
And what happened?

21:32.693 --> 21:36.697
Well, you couldn't find your
keys, and then you couldn't
find the hospital.

21:36.730 --> 21:39.099
And then you didn't
know how to drive.

21:39.132 --> 21:42.703
I know what happened.

21:42.736 --> 21:45.939
I panicked. I always panic.

21:45.972 --> 21:48.474
Well, cousin, you know... Blow.

21:54.380 --> 21:57.417
You know,
you had a real good plan.

21:57.450 --> 22:01.421
Don't patronize me.

22:01.454 --> 22:04.958
When somebody really
needed me to do something
really important...

22:04.991 --> 22:07.093
...I was worthless.

22:07.127 --> 22:09.563
I am worthless.

22:13.099 --> 22:14.601
Well, if you say so.

22:18.805 --> 22:22.776
Did I tell you that I'm going
to help Gina find an apartment?

22:22.809 --> 22:24.578
I think we're going to look
on Delaney Street.

22:29.950 --> 22:32.619
On Delaney Street?

22:32.653 --> 22:34.921
Delaney Street is all wrong.

22:34.955 --> 22:38.058
‐It is?
‐Absolutely wrong.

22:38.091 --> 22:41.562
Gina needs to be in a
neighborhood with good
public transportation.

22:41.595 --> 22:43.630
I never thought of that.

22:43.664 --> 22:47.467
She has to be within walking
distance of a supermarket.

22:47.500 --> 22:50.070
I never thought
of that, either.

22:50.103 --> 22:51.938
And what about a daycare center?

22:51.972 --> 22:54.708
This takes a lot of planning.
I'd better go with you.

22:54.741 --> 22:57.644
But that's a wonderful idea.

22:57.678 --> 23:00.747
Gina's very lucky to have
a worthless person like
you to help her.

23:06.620 --> 23:09.823
I see what you're doing.

23:09.856 --> 23:12.593
You're trying to give me
a false sense of self‐worth.

23:15.461 --> 23:18.632
Dirty trick, huh?

23:18.665 --> 23:21.434
Yeah.

23:21.467 --> 23:23.804
And I appreciate it.

23:23.837 --> 23:25.506
Cousin....

23:30.043 --> 23:33.113
You know, in Mypos,
we have a saying:

23:33.146 --> 23:34.548
[SPEAKING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

23:42.889 --> 23:44.691
Hits home, doesn't it?

23:49.262 --> 23:51.665
It says:

23:51.698 --> 23:54.034
"If everyone knew how
to herd sheep,

23:54.067 --> 23:55.736
there would be no one
to write poetry."

24:01.141 --> 24:04.911
Do you know what that means?

24:04.945 --> 24:07.781
It means we can't all be good
at everything,

24:07.814 --> 24:10.917
and that's OK.

24:10.951 --> 24:13.019
So that's what it means.

24:18.024 --> 24:21.762
What do you say you
and I go out and celebrate
this baby's birthday?

24:21.795 --> 24:24.931
Well, you don't have to
ask me once.

24:24.965 --> 24:27.901
Let's go out and paint the town
red, white and blue.

24:31.104 --> 24:34.875
But first,
let's put on our pants.

24:34.908 --> 24:36.777
Good plan. Good plan.
